<DOC><DOCNO> AP890727-0132 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2121EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-TaxCheats     07-27 0206</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Tax Cheats,200</SECOND><HEAD>Wealthiest Taxpayers Are Biggest Cheats, Study Says</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The federal government could collect billionsof dollars in unpaid taxes if it had the staff to auditupper-income Americans, who account for a disproportionate share oftax evasion, says a study sponsored by a Democratic group.   People who earn more than $50,000 a year, 12 percent of alltaxpayers, owed 40 percent of the $72.5 billion in taxes that wereowed to the government in 1985 but not collected, said the study,which was based on data from the Internal Revenue Service.   The top 3 percent of taxpayers, those who make more than$100,000 a year, accounted for 26 percent of the unpaid taxes, thestudy said. It was financed by Leadership for the New Century, agroup of progressive Democrats.   The study was based on detailed audits of 50,000 to 60,000Americans the IRS conducts every three years to determine how welltaxpayers are complying with the law.   People who earn less than $25,000 a year, 62 percent of alltaxpayers, owed 30 percent of the government's uncollected taxes in1985, the study said. Taxpayers who make $25,000 to $50,000 a yearaccounted for 31 percent of the unpaid taxes.</TEXT></DOC>